The statistical analysis of the results is based on a likelihood ratio test [68] using the CLs\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$_\mathrm {s}$$\end{document} method [69]. The parameter of interest is the signal strength, defined as the cross-section of the hypothetical contribution from physics beyond the SM in units of the cross-section of the benchmark model. The likelihood function is constructed from Poisson probability distributions of counting experiments for each of the six channels in each signal region. The systematic uncertainties are treated as nuisance parameters implemented in the likelihood functions with Gaussian constraints.

